Discussions between women on human rights and barriers to reproductive health care, for example, are not standardized. In these countries, there is a continuous feeling of shame about these topics, stemming from religious and cultural rules on privacy.

Yet, communication and connection are important elements for building a solid human rights culture. Without dialogue and respect, societal and individual problems can only be partially solved by legislation written “on paper.” The debate on #MeToo is a good example. This debate is not new, as many previous research studies have documented that women who are subjected to sexual violence do not talk open-ly about it. For women from conservative cultures, however, the debate has even more weight since sharing experiences can clash with customary practices and beliefs. First of all, women need to know that these practices are not normal and should be fought against. Second, they need to know that their experiences are not peculiar to them, personal and shameful. There are many people, both men and women, fighting for equality in Tunisia with me and there are also many women who have decided to speak out publicly through social media. I received many messages from women with similar stories, who decided to share them a decade after I did, or published critical messages on public figures.
